\begin_layout Itemize
According to the accounting rule, the COGS and SG&A already 
\series bold
include
\series default
 the depreciation for the relevant items.
 Thus, subtracting them from the gross profit yields the EBIT.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
As far as depreciation is concerned, there is an underlying assumption that
 the current balance is constructed of different periods, thus it is depreciated
 on the average (
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

half-life
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

).
 In reality, the best thing would be to go a few years back and take investments
 starting from there.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Mid-year discounting
\series default
: as in reality cash dlow is not generated at the end of the year but continuous
ly, it is more reasonable to discount using half of the discount rate 
\begin_inset Formula $(1+r)^{0.5}$
\end_inset

 (or 1.5, 2.5, ...) - then the 
\series bold
discount factor 
\series default
can be calculated.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Enterprise Value
\series default
 is different for short-term / long-term.
 The short-term EV consists of the sum of the next 5 years.
 The long-term EV is calculated according to the frowing perpetuity model.
 As it is delayed, it needs to be discounted to the present.
\end_layout

