\begin_layout Section
Forecasting Cash Flows - Continued
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Almost no firm can be consistently above the growth rate in the long-term.
 On average, all the firms converge to a nominal growth rate of about 5%.
 Having understood that, we can imply that in the long-term the growth rate
 is mostly capped by the industry/market/economy/population growth rate
 (e.g diapers market).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The long-term growth rate will be the multiplication of 2 numbers: the reinvestm
ent rate and the ROIC.
 RONIC is sometimes used as the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

return on 
\series bold
new
\series default
 invested capital
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In most of actual valuations, the capex and the depreciation are assumed
 to almost converge in a representative year.
 But this implication generates an 
\series bold
internal inconsistency
\series default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When reading a valution, the relationship between the 
\series bold
NOPAT
\series default
 and the 
\series bold
FCF
\series default
 is of importance.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Assuming the FCF is almost equal to the NOPAT means that there is almost
 no reinvestment (the payout ratio is close to 100%).
 Therefore, even without knowing anything particular about the firm - having
 too high FCF contradicts the assumption about the growth rate.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Having an assumption of a long-term growth for a company which does not
 invest does not make sense.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Assuming particular vlaues for the long-term growth rate and the ROIC, the
 FCF or a representative year can be calculated and the plugged in the long-term
 EV calculation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
WACC
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The WACC is among the most discussed items in the valuation, as it might
 have dramatic impact on it.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Yet the cash flows are actually more imporatnt than it.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When discounting the operational FCF, there are 2 candidates for the cost
 of capital: the 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{a}$
\end_inset

 (return on assets, which is also called 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{e}^{u}$
\end_inset

 - return on equity in an unlevered firm) and the WACC.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
By the M&M model, 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{L}=V_{U}+D\cdot t_{c}$
\end_inset

.
 Discounting by 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{u}^{e}$
\end_inset

 will yield the 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{U}$
\end_inset

, then the debt value component must be added manually.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If discounting with WACC instead - the levered value will be directly obtained.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In practice, using WACC is usually easier, and the separate values of 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{U}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $D\cdot t_{c}$
\end_inset

 are usually irrelevant.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The WACC is given by:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
WACC=\frac{E}{E+D}r_{E}+\frac{D}{E+D}r_{D}(1-t_{c})
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{D}{E+D}$
\end_inset

 raio is sometimes called 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

gearing
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Market Value of Equity
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The market value of equity can be estimated by multiplying the number of
 outstanding share by the market price of a share.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Market Value of Debt
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The net debt is the debt, excluding cash & cash equivalents.
 It is important to always use the 
\series bold
market
\series default
 value consistently.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Determining of the market value of the debt might not be trivial.
 When the market value is not available, the amortization table of loans
 can be used to determine the present value.
 In practice, it is usually replaced by the book value of the firm's debts.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Unless dealing with an extremely insolvent firm, trying to estimate the
 market value of debt won't give any added value, as it is not far form
 the book value.
 Thus in most cases simply using the book value is appropriate.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Though, in case there are many bonds trading in the market - looking at
 them is better.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There is no such thing as 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

negative net debt
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and putting a negative sign on it does not make sense - it simply means
 having excess financial assets.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Tax Rate
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When evaluating the whole firm, usually the average tax rate is used.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Return on Debt
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $r_{D}$
\end_inset

 has to be the 
\series bold
marginal 
\series default
expected borrowing cost of the firm - but it might be hard ot determine.
 Some alternatives can be used:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Ratio of current interest payments to the average debt
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Using the (rating-adjusted) yield curve
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The expected return on the firm's bonds (
\begin_inset Formula $\neq$
\end_inset

YTM)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $r_{D}\leq WACC\leq r_{E}$
\end_inset

 - getting a contradiction means an error in the calculation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The YTM is the average annual yield on a bond, if waiting until maturity
 and if the debt is indeed fully paid back.
 It is 
\series bold
not
\series default
 the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

expected
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 return, but the best possible outcome.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Therefore, using the YTM as 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{D}$
\end_inset

 is, 
\series bold
by definition
\series default
, wrong.
 The YTM is actually the expected value of 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{D}$
\end_inset

, plus the average loss on the bond.
\end_layout

